// @test: run
// @level: L0
// @tier: 2
// @tags: codegen, aot, protocol-dispatch, receiver-narrowing
// @timeout: 360000
// @skip: blocked by #76 — protocol-method dispatch picks wrong impl under AOT
// @expected-stdout: v4
// @expected-exit: 0
// @description: AOT protocol-method dispatch — SocketAddr.to_socket_addrs.
//
// 2026-04-26 #76 minimal repro: `addr.to_socket_addrs()` on a directly-
// constructed `SocketAddr` corrupts the resulting list — subsequent
// `is_ipv4()` SEGVs reading offset 0 of null. ALL of these adjacent
// paths PASS under AOT:
//
//   1. `SocketAddr.new_v4(...)` constructor + direct `.is_ipv4()`
//   2. `*addr` (deref of `&SocketAddr`)
//   3. Manual list build: `let mut v: List<SocketAddr> = []; v.push(addr)`
//      followed by `for sa in v { sa.is_ipv4() }`
//   4. Free function `fn my_to_addrs(s: &SocketAddr) -> Result<...>`
//      with body identical to the trait impl
//
// Only the trait protocol-method invocation `addr.to_socket_addrs()`
// (which dispatches via VBC `CallM` → method-dispatch table) fails.
// Same family as #79/#153 receiver-narrowing miss, but for protocol
// methods rather than inherent unwrap.
//
// Inline workaround comment at core/net/addr.vr:844-848 acknowledges
// the bug class: "the same call site emits 'field index 2 (offset
// 16+8 = 24) exceeds object data size 8' panics through the SocketAddr
// branch only." Aligning all `Iter` types to `List<SocketAddr>` was
// the workaround attempt — insufficient.
//
// Controlling blocker for #59 (HTTP/1.1 server bring-up) and downstream
// #61/#62 — `TcpListener.bind` cannot succeed because it routes through
// `to_socket_addrs` then iterates the result.
//
// REMOVE @skip once the dispatcher in
// `crates/verum_vbc/src/interpreter/dispatch_table/handlers/method_dispatch.rs`
// (or `crates/verum_vbc/src/codegen/expressions.rs.compile_method_call`
// receiver-narrowing path at lines ~6020-6051) correctly picks the
// `implement ToSocketAddrs for SocketAddr` impl rather than falling
// through to the `Text` impl.
//
// SCOPE NOTE (T0242): the STANDALONE braced-mount resolution leg — a
// `mount core.net.addr.{SocketAddr, Ipv4Addr, ToSocketAddrs};` in a file
// with no accompanying `mount core.*;` glob — used to fail E402 and was
// a co-blocker on un-skipping this spec. That leg is RESOLVED and now
// passes at interp; it is pinned by
// `vcs/specs/L0-critical/modules/mount_braced_type_from_archive_submodule.vr`
// (the interp-tier mount-form of this test, which exercises the same
// `to_socket_addrs()` body and prints `v4`). The @skip above therefore
// stands for the AOT protocol-DISPATCH bug ALONE — the only remaining
// reason this tier-2 spec is skipped.

mount core.*;
mount core.net.addr.{SocketAddr, Ipv4Addr, ToSocketAddrs};
mount core.io.stdio.{println};

fn main() -> Int {
    let addr = SocketAddr.new_v4(Ipv4Addr.localhost(), 8080);
    match addr.to_socket_addrs() {
        Ok(addrs) => {
            for sa in addrs {
                if sa.is_ipv4() {
                    println("v4");
                } else {
                    println("not v4");
                }
            }
            0
        }
        Err(_) => {
            println("err");
            1
        }
    }
}
